Introduktion:We Effect har inkommit med en anskan om rambidrag fr 2017 p sammanlagt SEK 188 033 400 fr en ettrig frlngning av det program som genomfrs under ramanslaget 2014-2016. Sida har drfr beslutat att bereda insatsen som ett kompletterande insatsbeslut. Sida bedmer att anskan r relevant under den nya strategin fr std genom Svenska organisationer i det civila samhllet (CSO-strategin) 2016-2022 och beslutar om ett bidrag om 180 000 000 SEK. Anskande organisation: We Effect r en ideell, partipolitiskt och religist obunden organisation vars syfte r att strka medlemsbaserade och demokratiska organisationers frmga att gra det mjligt fr fattiga kvinnor och mn att frbttra sina levnadsvillkor, frsvara sina rttigheter och bidra till ett rttvist samhlle. We Effect bildades 1958 och har varit ramorganisation sedan 1978 under namnet Kooperation Utan Grnser. Organisationen r en demokratiskt strukturerad frening och bakom We Effect str ett sextiotal medlemsorganisationer frn den svenska konsument- och producentkooperationen. We Effect r en vletablerad organisation i det svenska samhllet, med ett ppet och demokratiskt arbetsstt - och med en stark internationell frankring.We Effects vision r en hllbar och rttvis vrld fri frn fattigdom och organisationen arbetar inom landsbygdsutveckling och bostder, inkluderat rtten till mark, jmstlldhet och finansiella tjnster. Anskan omfattar 17 program p regional eller landniv och ett globalt program som totalt bestr av 160 projekt i 24 lnder. Sida beslutade 2014 att frnya We Effects status som ramorganisation. Anskan:Anskan bygger p We Effects prioriteringar och fljer logiskt p tidigare verksamhet. We Effects ramanskan fr 2017 r en fortsttning p det ramprogram som genomfrs under pgende ramavtal 2014-2016.Syftet med stdet r att strka partnerorganisationen som sdan och att detta i sin tur kar organisationens frmga att  ena sidan pverka och krva frndring p makroniv/strukturell niv och,  andra sidan erbjuda medlemmarna efterfrgade tjnster. Enligt We Effects frndringsteori genomfrs den huvudsakliga verksamheten av partnerorganisationerna. Inom programmen fr landsbygdsutveckling stdjer We Effect bondeorganisationer i deras arbete med att ka sina medlemmars inkomster och tillgng till mat genom t.ex. jordbruksrdgivning, strkt position p marknaden och hjlp med frhandlingar om priser. Organisationen fresprkar ett hllbart och klimatanpassat jordbruk och stdjer ocks lokala spar- och kreditfreningar som gr det mjligt fr lantbrukare med sm resurser att spara och lna pengar samt f tillgng till frskringar. Inom bostadsprogrammen arbetar We Effect med lokala bostadskooperativ dr medlemmarna tillsammans bygger sina bostder. Kooperativen bedriver pverkansarbete fr tillgng till bostadskrediter och skrad rtt till mark att bygga p. Jmstlldhet r ett prioriterat omrde fr We Effects verksamhet. We Effect strvar efter att integrera jmstlldhet i all verksamhet och organisationen stdjer partnerorganisationernas arbete med att strka kvinnors rttigheter, bland annat genom kvinnligt ledarskap, en mer rttvis arbetsfrdelning i jordbruket samt genom att frsvara kvinnors rtt till mark. Mlgruppen fr We Effects utvecklingssamarbete r kvinnor och mn som lever i fattigdom och som r medlemmar, eller potentiella medlemmar, i kooperativa organisationer, andra demokratiska freningar eller informella grupper vilka arbetar fr att uppn gemensamma ml.Frvntade resultat:We Effects anskan har resultatmatriser p land- och regional niv, med indikatorer och utgngsvrden. P global niv finns en resultatmatris men utan aggregerade utgngs- och mlvrden. Anskan har fljande ml:1. Std till kapacitetsutveckling: Strkt kapacitet hos aktrer i det civila samhllet i utvecklingslnder att arbeta rttighetsbaserat i sina roller som rstbrare och organisatr av tjnster.Prioriterade mlgrupper fr kapacitetsutvecklingen r organisationer, ntverk och rrelser som representeras av eller agerar med legitimitet i relation till kvinnor, mn, ungdomar och barn som lever i fattigdom och/eller r diskriminerade. Flickors och kvinnors rttigheter, deltagande och inflytande ska srskilt uppmrksammas. 2. Std till demokratisering och mnskliga rttigheter i utvecklingslnder inom alla sektorer: Strkt demokratisering och kad respekt fr fattiga och diskriminerade mnniskors mnskliga rttigheter.Stdet ska inriktas p att strka gruppers och individers mjlighet att sjlva kunna utkrva sina rttigheter och pverka sina livsvillkor. Fokus ska vara rollerna fr CSO i utvecklingslnder som rstbrare och, under vissa frutsttningar, som organisatr av tjnster. Tidigare resultatuppfyllelse:Sida har mngrig verlag positiv erfarenhet av samarbete med We Effect. Insatsen r i stora drag en fortsttning p liknande verksamhet som Sida tidigare har bedmt generera signifikanta och relevanta civilsamhllestrkande och fattigdomsbekmpande resultat. 2009 genomfrdes p uppdrag av Sida en jmfrande studie av 42 utvrderingar som We Effect genomfrt under perioden 2006-2008. Studien lyfte relevanta resultat p bde output- och outcome-niv. I all rapportering (senast i slutrapporten 2010-2012) till Sida finns mnga exempel p bra och omfattande resultat i linje med CSO-strategin och jmstlldhetspolicyn inom We Effects prioriterade omrden. Mot bakgrund av erfarenheten av tidigare samarbete och uppndda resultat bedmer Sida att We Effect kommer att kunna garantera kvalitet och effektivitet i programmet.Grund fr Sidas bedmning: Sida baserar denna bedmning p bedmningen av anskan fr 2014-2016, samt rliga rapporter, revisioner, mten och reserapporter fr uppfljningsbesk under samma period.Bedmningsprocess:Eftersom insatsen bereds som ett kompletterande insatsbeslut har beredningen i s stor utstrckning som mjligt utgtt frn den omfattande beredning som gjordes av anskan fr den pgende avtalsperioden 2014-2016. I de fall bedmningen som gjordes av anskan 2014-2016 fortsatt r relevant har denna behllits och endast en kompletterande kommentar gllande 2017 har lagts till. I vissa fall, s som t.ex. bedmningen av de tv senaste revisionsrapporterna, r bedmningen som gjordes i beredningen av den frra anskan inte lngre relevant, varfr en ny bedmning gjorts. Insatshanteringssystemet Trac har ocks frndrats sedan 2013 d beredningen av anskan 2014-2016 gjordes vilket gr att det tillkommit frgor som inte fanns d. I beredningen anges vilka bedmningar som gjorts i beredningen av anskan 2014-2016 och vilka som tillkommit i beredningen av anskan 2017. Srskilt fokus i beredningen har legat p fljande frgor:- Mjlighet fr We Effects nuvarande organisationsstruktur och ledarskapssammansttning att kontinuerligt utmana sig sjlv och positionera sig fr att inom relevanta omrden och lnder pverka den framtida internationella utvecklingen.- Genomfrandet och effektiviteten av operativa frbttringar kring HRBA, jmstlldhet, milj och klimat, korruption, harmonisering, bistndseffektivitet, kvalitetsskring och srskilt konflikt och risk.

Effect arbetar i 25 lnder och har ett flertal landkontor. De har ven fyra regionkontor i fyra vrldsdelar. Nedan fljer ngra exempelpuppndda resultat inom de olika program som We Effect bedriver inom respektive region. Fr mer utfrlig information om uppndda resultathnvisas till dox 13/001154.
Exempel frn Latinamerika
Regional Housing and Habitat Programme (VIVHA) / Strengthened networks and alliances between organisations and key actors (men and women)
National land access policies approved and implemented
The issue of land was completely invisible in the region at the beginning of the programme. VIVHA brought this issue to the table and has achieved progress in the last four years. For example, the approval of a land bank in various municipalities in Nicaragua, the Land and Property Law in the historic centre and the laws approved for territorial regulation in El Salvador, and in Paraguay, funding was achieved for housing construction and the reactivation of a land portfolio. Organisations will continue to expand the model and legal frameworks that favour them, however the use and permanence of state resources must be guaranteed. The cooperative movement should continue working both with the cooperatives that have built housing, as well as those who still do not have housing to create a movement that can defend its achievements.
Strengthened community life
At least 25 initiatives for income generation have been implemented and are functioning in the region, for example savings and credit initiatives, some of which serve to pay loans, or community stores that provide youth with employment opportunities; there are also activities to decrease the time women dedicate to care work in the home. The housing projects that have been built have the necessary legal and formal environmental processes and the cooperatives have piloted environmental practices such as the use of alternative materials, recycling, organic agriculture, among other things. However, the programme considers that this is not enough; it is necessary to grow the use of alternative materials through the support of environmental laws and policies such as regional water and food sovereignty laws with the goal of holistically defending habitat.
Exempel frn Sdra Afrika
Regional Gender Equality Programme (GEP)
In Malawi, theland bill was finally enacted in 2016 into law. There is a customary land act, which also promote women's rights among other things thereby enabling women to be part of village land management committees as well as village land tribunals, which are the decision-making structures on land administration. WOLREC was part of the delegation that lobbied the President to assent to the bill as there were opposing voices. The President was convinced that having that law in place would protect women's rights.
Exempel frn stra afrika
Regional Housing Programme: Right to Adequate Housing in Eastern Africa (RHEA)
Pamoja Trust in Kenya, after the adoption of the Slum Upgrading and Prevention policy, jointly with other CSO went around the country popularizing the policy. County governments were able to appreciate the structures for implementing the policy and undertook to establish the same.

Regional Financial Services Programme: Financial Institutions Reaching the Marginalized (FIRM)
The number of youth accessing financial services increased from 121,960 to over 300,000 during 2017. Out of this number, there is no significant difference between female and male youth engaged. This is to imply that the issues affecting youth affected them in the same manner regardless of their sex. The financial institutions also developed specific products to target the youth. Specifically, the Increased Co-operators Access to Financial Services (ICAFIS) project in Uganda led to great increase in youth participation through the promotion of youth savings clubs in schools.This has led to improvement in savings culture of the students as well as improving their skills to manage their clubs such as record keeping, accounting and reporting.
In Africa, the International Cooperative Alliance (ICA) office is working to ensure co-operative organisations get support from their governments in the continent by creating conducive guidelines that promote co-operative development. The latest developments that the office is following keenly include: Kenya, review of the cooperative acts is underway. Ghana, have reviewed their act and the bill is about to be tabled in Parliament. Mozambique, has started working on their cooperative policy. Uganda, the MP are vigorously lobbying the government to allocate budget for the revival of the Cooperative Bank.The idea of the promoting Cooperative Banks in the continent is imperative and the office so far has organised one consultative meeting to advocate for the same, to foster financial inclusion and cooperative development.
Together with ILO, ICA carried out a rapid assessment for cooperatives competitiveness potential for export and import in selected SADC countries. The report from the study has been released and several policy directions will be informed by the study. ICA is also finalizing a study on the review of existing information and communication technologies in cooperatives in Africa to establish a user-friendly integrated management information system. The aim of the study is gauge uptake of ICT in their operations.

Exempel frn Europa
EU Alignment and Empowerment of Civil Society Organisations in Albania, Macedonia, Moldova, Kosovo and Bosnia Herzegovina
Some negative trends in terms of democratic freedoms have been observed and these negative trends have had a negative impact overall on the civil society sector and the CSO ability to act as voice for their members.
In terms of outreach, the programme has overachieved the target and the number of direct and indirect rights-holders have increased more than planned. In 2017, the programme directly involved 274 different type of organisations in associations and cooperatives. The number of direct beneficiaries has reached 93.367, out of which 46.190 men & 47.177 women.The programme also achieved its target of at least 5o% of rights-holders being women, 53.75% of the programme resources reached women and 50.5% of direct rights-holders are women. Direct observations, internal and external evaluations of the projects within the frame in the programme and the interviews conducted with the final beneficiaries during the monitoring missions shows improved perception of the socio-economic situation among the members of the targeted communities and groups, thanks to their active involvement in the programme / project activities.There is an evident improvement of the capacity of We Effect to work with social inclusion and minority rights, taking into consideration the establishment of fruitful cooperation between the partners in Macedonia, Kosovo and Albania that are working with Roma minorities.During 2017, We Effect supported the formalisation of the Balkan Rural Development Network, lifting issues of rural development also to a regional level.

Exempel frn Asien
Strengthening member-based organisations to fight poverty and injustice in rural areas of Southeast Asia (SEA)
We Effects team has discussed with partners how to influence policies in favour of the target farmers more effectively. As results, partner organisations have facilitated target FO to obtain total 6 new services provided by government and successfully got approval for 15 policies/ government projects benefiting the target FO and their farmers. Some are highlighted such as the approval for registration of the Siem Reap AC Union (Cambodia), two decisions made by the Yen Bai Provincial Peoples Committee on supporting development of AC in the province and supporting to gain Fair Trade certificate for Suoi Giang tea (Vietnam), provision of agricultural extension services to target Coops (Myanmar), and number of loans granted to target farmers in all three countries. It is noticed that most of advocacy efforts limit at local level and specifically to the target FO, while policy and institutional changes at regional and national level are not yet reached.'

Exempel frn Vi-skogens verksamhet
The FOA programme goal of improving the living conditions for farmer households through sustainable use of natural resources within the Lake Victoria Basin were being achieved through six programme components with thirteen outcomes.
Vi Agroforestry has put much focus on strengthening the capacity of partner farmer organisations in areas such as leadership and governance, visioning and strategic planning, as well as technical aspects such as human resource, financial management, agroforestry, environment etc. This has resulted in;
Increased efficiency in farmer organisations as they deliver services to their members. This has attracted more members to the partner farmer organisations which where therefore reaching more farmers.Increased democracy and transparency within the farmer organisations. The FOA programme has supported refining of rules and regulations that govern the farmer organisations. Partner farmer organisations are encouraged to hold annual general meetings (AGM). It is during the AGM that members receive the audited financial reports of the organisation, elect the officials to manage the organisation, ask questions and receive answers from the management of the organisation. The audited financial reports of the partner farmer organisations have seen remarkable improvement during the reporting period. Strengthened farmers organisations competencies and skills in resource mobilisation. During the year, partner farmer organisations continued with resource mobilisation from their members, businesses and donors. This has resulted in an average increase of 32% in assets per member of the partner farmer organisation (per capita assets) compared with the target of 20%.
Environment Agroforestry and Climate Change
Vi Agroforestry and partner farmer organisations continued capacity building farmers on various methods to reverse land degradation, such as adoption agroforestry and sustainable agriculture land management (SALM) practices and to adopt the use of energy saving devices and alternative energy. This has resulted in;
Decreased land degradation in the programme area by planting over 4.7 million long-term trees and 1.7 metres short-term trees. To curb soil erosion, 58, 373 households have constructed soil erosion control structures.Farmers have become more resilient to climate change through increased adoption of agroforestry and SALM practices (53%) which has contributed to 41% of households reporting yield increase. 82,421 household have diversified crops increasing their resilience to extreme climatic conditions.The programme area has 19,142 households using wood saving devices, 28,220 households using solar energy devices and 1,201 households using biogas. This has contributed to reduced stress on natural resources through increased production and improved utilisation of sustainable energy. The number of households using biogas has been progressively increase though at a slow rate due to lack of low cost technologies.

Avvikelser i planerad verksamhet:
Region Latinamerika
The technical partner IDESAC in Guatemala was evaluated due to reported irregularities. Based on the results of the evaluation and weak results in general, the decision was taken to terminate the relationship with the organisation and to directly support the grassroots cooperative organisation, MEGCOVAM.
The greatest deviation in the regional rural development programme was caused by the implementation of large projects financed by other donors that start and finish within CIVSAMs financial cycle, which greatly affected programme indicator behaviours and results. For example, the completion of the project Contributing to the Integral Economic Development in Guatemalan Rural Areas (DRIGUA), which was financed by the Embassy of Sweden in Guatemala and represented nearly 40 per cent of the programmes budget, greatly impacted 2015 and 2016 results.

Region stra Afrika
The only significant deviation for Eastern Africa was as a result of the shrinking civic space. The increased government control of financial institutions in Tanzania impacted on theWe Effect partner, Meru Community Bank, which went into liquidation at the beginning of 2018.

Region Sdra Afrika
The ongoing political and economic challenges in Zimbabwe resulted in the housing organisation ZINAHCO being phased out in 2016 because it was difficult for the partner to operate.We Effect continued to monitor the situation throughout 2017. However, there were ongoing challenges for housing cooperatives in Zimbabwe, including the announcement to ban housing cooperatives.
Many We Effect partners in Mozambique are operating in areas affected by the ongoing political and armed conflict. Although partners resumed work in 2017, restrictions still applied. We Effect mitigated the impact on the work of partners by providing conflict analysis training.
The minor deviation in the regional housing programme, RAHSA, concerned the partner CCODE.We Effect phased out financial support and as a result, CCODE did not carry about planned activities in 2017. The decision to phase out funding in the partner organisation was made in consultation with the We Effect Malawi office and the Regional Director after an in-depth audit had established financial weaknesses and areas of non-compliance. All funds that CCODE could not account for after the audit were repaid to We Effect by the end of the year.

Region Europa
There were no significant deviations on a programme level and all planned activities were realized according to the operational plans. A few minor deviations have been identified at partner project level, but not to the extent that they can be considered to have affected the overall implementation of the projects.

Region Asien
There have been few significant deviations in Asia during the reporting period and the sub-programs in the region  Palestine, South East Asia, Sri Lanka and The Philippines  have been implemented according to plan.
Minor deviations concern termination and phase-out of partnerships. In Palestine a decision was made not to proceed with a piloted partnership with the local organisation SEC, as the partner assessment concluded that the organisation had internal democracy issues and lacked commitment to the strategic objectives and values of We Effect. We Effect also decided to phase out another partner, Palestinian Cooperative Education Institute (PCEI) . In Sri Lanka, one of the partners, MONLAR, had for an extended period had operational issues affecting both program implementation and its capacity to submit financial and progress reports on time. This together with other factors such as a shift in the organisations strategic direction, led We Effect to re-consider the continuation of the partnership in the next program cycle. During the year, MONLAR was supported in developing an exit strategy to ensure the sustainability of the organisation and the results achieved.

Vi-skogen
There was an ambition in 2017 to implement the Lake Victoria Farmer Organisations Agroforestry (FOA) Programme through a consortia model, one in each of the four countries. However, due to practical problems to ensure program quality and in bringing in new partners, Vi Agroforestry reverted to a bilateral partnership approach.
The FOA programme had planned to increase the resources channelled to partners. This target was not met since one partner, KENAFF, responded to audit recommendations in a way that resulted in suspension of funding in 2017.

Insatsen har under perioden 2014-2017 haft goda resultat i bde i termer av strkt kapacitet hos Svenska kyrkans lokala partners, samt mnga konkreta utvecklingseffekter,inomprogrammets olika mlomrden. Majoriteten lokala partners inom insatsen har som en fljd av sin strkta kapacitet ingtt flerriga avtal med Svenska kyrkan under det nya ramavtalet som slts med Sida fr perioden 2018-2022. Exempel p konkreta utvecklingseffekter av insatsen r att Svenska kyrkans lokala CSO-partners direkt bidragit till fredsprocessen i Colombia 2016, samt till civilsamhllets rapportering om mnskliga rttigheter i samband med FNs UPR (Universal Periodic Review) i Syd-Sudan och i Myanmar 2015. Ett annat exempel r att samarbetet i Tanzania ftt som effekt att kyrkor utkat sin hlsoservice till kvinnor och att sexuella och reproduktiva rttigheter (SRHR) numera ingr, samt med frbttrad kvalitet,inom denordinarie hlsovrd som kyrkorna bidrar till.

vergripande frga: Resultat kopplat till avsedd effekt 2015Frga: Sammanfatta resultat relaterade till avsedd effekt (denna information kommer att skickas till Open Aid).Svar: I enlighet med beslut fattat av VU behver utvalda insatsml frn och med 2016-06-16 inte lngre fyllas i och om dessa ml finns sedan tidigare behver de inte heller fljas upp i uppfljningen. Sida vljer drfr att inte flja upp de tidigare utvalda insatsmlen i stllningstagandet till SMR:s slutrapport. Nedan fljer en vergripande bedmning av avsedd effekt och mluppfyllelse.

Mlet fr SMR:s utvecklingssamarbete r att bidra till utvecklingen av ett hllbart, rttvist, fredligt, jmstllt och demokratiskt samhlle i samarbetslnderna, dr de mnskliga rttigheterna respekteras, skyddas och uppfylls, genom std och kapacitetsutveckling till frndringsaktrer med legitimitet och frmga att arbeta rttighetsbaserat fr att utkrva ansvar av skyldighetsbrare och att strka rttighetsinnehavares organisering, egenmakt och frutsttningar att sjlva frndra sina livsvillkor.

SMR rapporterar relativt utfrligt om resultat inom detta ml och ger illustrativa exempel under varje delml. Ngra exempel p resultat r frndrad vapenlagstiftning som resultat av pverkansarbete i Venezuela, kad medvetenhet om barns rttigheter i skolor i DR Kongo, kad mobilisering i Uganda fr HIV-prevention, kvinnors egenmakt i familjen har strkts bland afghanska flyktingar i Iran och yrkesutbildning fr kvinnor i Palestina.

Sammanfattning av uppndda resultat 2015-2017
Fljande redogrelse fr exempel p uppndda resultat bygger frmst p Pingsmissionens utvecklingssamarbetes (PMU) slutrapportering fr perioden 2015-2017 (Dox dokumentnummer:016705/18), samt iakttagelser frn Sidas uppfljningsresa till Kenya i maj 2017.
Perioden har i hg grad prglats av den femriga strategi PMU antog 2016 (Kompassen) dr SDG 5 (jmstlldhet), SDG 16 (fredliga och inkluderande samhllen) samt den trosbaserade identiteten och dess bidrag till samhllsansvar frdjupats.
I relation till mlomrde 1 i CSO-strategin "Strkt kapacitet hos civilsamhllesorganisationer i utvecklingslnder" bedmer PMU att det r noterbart att medelvrdet fr alla indikationer i resultatmodellen visar p en frbttring, trots att PMU under perioden skrpte kriterierna fr partnerbedmningarna. Fokuserat under perioden var kapacitets- och kompetensutveckling inom jmstlldhet och pverkansarbete och PMU ser det som positivt att detta gett tydlig effekt. Sammantaget ser PMU att partners genom PMU:s std utvecklats positivt inom mnga omrden, bde internt och i sitt arbete gentemot verksamhetens mlgrupper.
I relation till mlomrde 2 i CSO-strategin "Ett gynnsamt samhllsklimat fr civilsamhllesorganisationer i utvecklingslnder" ser PMU en tydlig utveckling inom bland annat samverkan och engagemang i ntverk, politiskt pverkansarbete samt arbetet fr fred. Gllande demokrati ser PMU en tydlig positiv utveckling, med ett strkt demokrati- och fredsarbete, och frdjupat lrande bl.a. genom flera studier och utvrderingar. PMU noterar samtidigt ett krympande demokratiskt utrymme och ett kat behov av fredsbyggande insatser i allt fler lnder. Mnga samarbetspartners bedms vara bra p att skapa mtesplatser mellan olika etniska och religisa grupper, samt mellan utsatta grupper och ansvarsbrare p olika niver.
Gllande jmstlldhet (byggsten 2) ser PMU mnga goda resultat under perioden, t.ex. inom bearbetning av knsroller samt inom flickors och kvinnors rttigheter, organisering och deltagande. Resultat som lyfts fram r bland annat att kvinnor i hgre utstrckning tar plats som ledare och i olika beslutsfattande positioner. Vidare rapporteras tydliga resultat inom motverkandet av skadliga kulturella traditioner som t.ex. knsstympning, samt inom kvinnors rtt att besluta ver sin egen kropp. PMU noterar ocks tydliga kopplingar till kapacitets- och kompetensutveckling som sker genom det globala projektet och ambassadrprogrammet. PMU:s arbete med mainstreaming har ftt tydligt genomslag under perioden, vilket bland annat visas av att 87 % av projekt med resultat inom jmstlldhet inte hade detta tema som primrt fokus.
Inom hlsa, utbildning och frsrjning (byggsten 3) ser PMU en positiv utveckling resultatmssigt. Lokala partners kan genom sina ntverk och genom programbaserade ansatser skerstlla att alla tre komponenter i byggstenen samverkar, vilket tydligt pverkar fattigdomen i lokala kontexter. Vldigt ofta kopplar resultaten inom hlsa, utbildning och frsrjning till resultat inom jmstlldhet, t.ex. inom mdrahlsovrd och skadliga kulturella traditioner. Verksamheten som resultatrapporteras inom byggsten 3 r ocks tydligt lnkad till demokratiml och fredliga samhllen.
Inom milj (byggsten 4) ser PMU tydligt att mainstreaming-arbetet fungerat vl under perioden. PMU noterar en tydlig kning av resultat bde kvantitativt och kvalitativt, p alla tre samhllsniver.
Vid Sidas uppfljningsresa i Kenya i maj 2017 beskte Sida PMU:s partnerorganisation Free Pentecostal Fellowship in Kenya (FPFK), som bland annat driver projekt inom barnrttsfrgor i syfte att strka barns rttigheter i det kenyanska samhllet. Sida noterade fljande resultat under uppfljningen:

The ICRC is one of the worlds largest humanitarian organizations, with activities in around 100 countries. Throughout the agreement period of this contribution the ICRC has successfully responded to needs in some of the world's most difficult places, including in hard-to-reach areas across Afghanistan, Myanmar, Nigeria, South Sudan and Yemen. The ICRC was also successful in adapting their response in light of the COVID-19 pandemic, albeit with some challenges in reaching all of the planned results. Throughout the four-year activity period, the ICRC has for example: - Reached around 20 million people with food aid; - Distributed basic household items, such as blankets, mats, cooking sets and hygiene kits, to more than 20 million people; - Supported hundreds of hospitals and health facilities around the globe;- Influenced several countries to adopt or amend domestic statues to implement IHL and/or other relevant instruments; - Trained members of the military, police and non-state armed groups in IHL; - Helped arrange thousands of phone calls to inform families of the whereabouts of a detained relative;In summary, the ICRC has been successful in protecting the lives and dignity of victims of armed conflict and other situations of violence and to provide them with assistance.

Vidare rapporterades goda resultat frn ett projekt mnat att ka kunskapen om HIV och AIDS, mnskliga rttigheter och demokratiseringsprocesser bland unga i Kenya och Uganda. Forum Syd finansierade ven en insats i Uganda som syftade till att strka kvinnors inflytande i demokratiska institutioner och bidra till deras ekonomiska oberoende. Frstrkt ekonomisk stllning uppnddes bland annat genom praktisk trning och engagemang i olika inkomstgenerarande aktiviteter s som skrdderi, uppfdning av getter, jordbruk och smskaligt egenfretagande. 
Slutsatsen frn resultatmodellen visar att majoriteten av insatserna resulterade i frndrade attityder bland rttighetsinnehavare samt en kad frmga att krva rttigheter. Modellen visade ven en frstrkt mobiliseringskraft och kad organisation av mlgrupperna vilket i sin tur skulle kunna generera en kad medlemsbas och/eller skapandet av nya civilsamhllsorganisationer. Totalt nddes 14 av de 17 indikatorer som Forum Syd anvnde i sin resultatmodell, vilket motsvarar ca 82 procent.
De indikatorer som visade smre resultat rrde i synnnerhet frndringar bland ansvarsbrare i form av lag och moraliska skyldigheter. Dessa resultat motsvarar ca 18 procent av Forum Syds resultatmodell. Indikatorerna 'Tillmpning av lagar och internationella konventioner', 'Lagstiftning', och 'Betydande bidrag till utvidgandet av det demokratiska utrymmet' visade mycket lga niver och ndde ej de ml som angetts i Forum Syds anskan. Programes and projects results 2022I-  NRC increased 24.4% its budget in 2022 compared to 2021 and received incomes for 2022 that are 26% above the budgeted target. Sida remains NRC's 4th donor after the Norwegian MFA, ECHO and BHA, in volume with 7.5% of your income.- Flexible funding represents in average 19% of NRC's resources, with extremes in Afghanistan (8%) and Cameroon (43%).- NRC worked with 9.8 million people in need of humanitarian assistance in 40 crisis settings, including 28 contexts with Sida's humanitarian funding for 2022: a level comparable to pre-pandemic situation. NRC has reported that it reached 8 596 818 persons in programes and projects funded by Sida/HUM in 2022.- The proportion of cash assistance continued to grow in 2022 compared to 2021 (4%); the growth was 24% from 2020 to 2021.- The need to invest further in preventing SEAH and fraud remains a high priority, as discussed with NRC earlier; Sida appreciates however NRCs transparency and due diligence on these matters.- The 2022 Global report on internal displacement (GRID) has focused on the relationship between climate change and forced displacement. The 2023 GRID is focusing on food insecurity as a driver, impact and potential barrier to solutions for internal displacement. The economic impacts of displacement are explored and analysed highlighting the relationship between food security and internal displacement in efforts to identify development solutions for IDP's across the world.- NRC joined the Core Humanitarian Standard (CHS) Alliance in 2022, formalizing its investment in programe quality and accountability to affected populations, strengthened local capacities, and community participation. - To meet the commitment to generate evidence and collect good practices on risk sharing, NRC is actively engaged in the Risk-Sharing Platform and aims to engage in next steps with the Risk-Sharing Framework, in particular with Sida as a key interlocutor among the humanitarian donor community. Every country programmes offer interesting results to highlight.

Below is an extract of results achieved in the past year, presented at the annual planning and review meeting that was held in Freetown in December 2022, gathering all the 17 program countries with staff represented by WHO AFRO WHO Country offices (WCOs) and Ministry of Health (MoH) staff on national level. For more results please see annual narrative report July 2021-July 2022 Dox 043460/22.Progress was made in all countries towards an enabling policy environment for Sexual and Reproductive Health and Rights (SRHR) services including abortion care through evidence-based advocacy and policy dialogue. These include the technical framework for the Safe Motherhood and Reproductive Health Bill developed in Sierra Leone in 2022; strengthened partnership, advocacy, and policy dialogue for SRHR, including the updating of the Regional Agenda for SRHR in line with the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) for the period 20222030 to serve as a guide for Member States and partners to advance SRHR; improved monitoring and accountability for SRHR through harmonized health facility assessments (HHFA); using tools that have integrated the SRHR/abortion module in Burkina Faso, Burundi, Cameroon, Central African Republic, Congo, Cte dIvoire, Democratic Republic of the Congo, and Ghana; development and/or updating of the national Sexual, Reproductive, Maternal, Child, Adolescent Health (SRMNCAH) scorecard in most of the program countries to monitor and assess  the continuity of essential SRHR services.  Some innovative approaches were shared, such as the establishment of a youth call centre on SRHR in Burundi, the incident management system to accelerate the reduction of maternal deaths in Cameroon, collaboration with professional associations of gynaecologists/obstetricians and midwives and other actors for dissemination and implementation of WHO guidelines in many of the program countries. Capacity-building sessions were also conducted in facilities, within communities, and in professional organizations in all the programme countries.
